oc:kn_345c0efc a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When the Kotlin code under test contains suspend functions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For suspending functions (coroutines), use `coEvery` / `coVerify` instead of `every` / `verify` in MockK. There is no direct coroutine support in Mockito." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Coroutine functions have a different signature and calling convention; MockK's co-prefixed variants handle the coroutine context correctly." .

oc:kn_5139f4ae a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting tests that use @InjectMocks" ;
    oc:directiveContent "MockK has no direct equivalent to @InjectMocks — use constructor injection instead. This is actually better design practice." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Constructor injection makes dependencies explicit and testable, aligning with Kotlin's preference for val constructor parameters." .

oc:kn_54f00af9 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting argument matchers" ;
    oc:directiveContent "MockK matches exact values by default, so `eq(x)` is often unnecessary. MockK's `any()` handles all Kotlin types including non-null types without extra configuration." ;
    oc:hasRationale "MockK's type inference and default matching behavior reduce verbosity compared to Mockito's explicit matchers." .

oc:kn_6e4c49e8 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting a Mockito test file to Kotlin" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Detect Mockito imports in source file. 2. Decide conversion target: MockK (full migration) or mockito-kotlin (syntax-only). 3. Replace mock creation: Mockito.mock → mockk<Foo>() or mock<Foo>(). 4. Replace stubbing: when().thenReturn → every {} returns or whenever().thenReturn. 5. Replace verification: verify(foo).bar() → verify { foo.bar() }. 6. Replace ArgumentCaptor with slot<T>() + capture(). 7. Inline mock initialization into property declarations, removing setUp methods. 8. Add coEvery/coVerify for suspend functions if converting to MockK." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_767b6dcb a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When testing suspend functions with MockK" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "kotlin" ;
    oc:directiveContent """// Coroutine support in MockK
 coEvery { foo.suspendBar() } returns x
 coVerify { foo.suspendBar() }""" .

oc:kn_83ad312e a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting Mockito stubbing to Kotlin" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use Mockito.`when`(...)` in Kotlin — use `whenever(...)` from mockito-kotlin or `every { ... } returns ...` from MockK to avoid backtick-escaping the `when` keyword." ;
    oc:hasRationale "`when` is a keyword in Kotlin and must be escaped with backticks, making code ugly and error-prone; the Kotlin-friendly wrappers eliminate this." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_83b1f992 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing MockK test code" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "kotlin" ;
    oc:directiveContent """// MockK stubbing
 every { foo.bar() } returns x
 every { foo.bar() } throws e
 every { foo.bar() } answers { /* answer block */ }
 justRun { foo.bar() }

 // Verification
 verify { foo.bar() }
 verify(exactly = 2) { foo.bar() }
 verify(exactly = 0) { foo.bar() }

 // Slot capture
 val slot = slot<Order>()
 verify { repo.save(capture(slot)) }
 slot.captured // accessed value""" .

oc:kn_9287970c a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When keeping Mockito but converting to Kotlin syntax" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "kotlin" ;
    oc:directiveContent """// mockito-kotlin stubbing
 import org.mockito.kotlin.mock
 import org.mockito.kotlin.whenever
 import org.mockito.kotlin.verify

 val repo = mock<PriceRepository>()
 whenever(repo.findPrice("ITEM-1")).thenReturn(9.99)
 verify(repo).findPrice("ITEM-1")""" .

oc:kn_cbf4d20f a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When Mockito imports are detected in a Java test file" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Only convert to MockK if the project already uses MockK or is doing a full Kotlin migration. If the project wants to keep Mockito, convert only the syntax using mockito-kotlin library (org.mockito.kotlin)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Forcing a MockK migration on a project that wants to stay with Mockito creates unnecessary churn and risk; mockito-kotlin provides idiomatic Kotlin wrappers without changing the mocking framework." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_dbca39d2 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When converting any Mockito test class" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Eliminate @Before setUp methods — initialize mocks inline with property declarations using reified generics (mockk<Foo>() or mock<Foo>()). This works because MockK and mockito-kotlin mocks do not require a runner." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inline initialization is more idiomatic Kotlin, reduces boilerplate, and avoids lifecycle coupling with test runners." .

oc:kn_dcabecad a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting conversion" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If converting to MockK: add dependency io.mockk:mockk. If keeping Mockito with Kotlin syntax: add dependency org.mockito.kotlin:mockito-kotlin." .

